<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-10-13T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-10-13T05:00:00-05:00" n="485" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d485">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/693: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-10-13T18:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">October 13,
                                        1927—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 13—4:50
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>926. Your [<hi rend="italic">My</hi>] 914. Following from American consul
                            at Canton: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“October 12, 10 a.m. Your 193 and October 8, 3 p.m. Joined
                                    consular colleagues this morning in protest against imposition
                                    of new tax. General Li plans discontinue tax.</p>
                                <p>The reply suggested adoption of the consular compulsory procedure
                                    adopted at Shanghai impossible at Canton. Imports discharged in
                                    native city, control of which could not be gained except by the
                                    use of force.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>